Extremes.
I am busted; I am busted;
Not a dollar to my name;
And with my forlorn condition,
Comes a sense of want and shame.
I am busted; nearly busted;
Joy for me has sadly flown;
For to give me cheer and comfort,
Fifty cents I do not own.
I am busted; badly busted;
Light of heart I cannot be;
For in all the tide of quarters,
Not a quarter comes to me.

I am busted; really busted;
And I feel such keen destress;
For among my other trifles,
Not a dime do I possess.
I am busted; sadly busted;
And it preys upon my mind;
For in all my many pockets,
Not a nickel do I find.
I am busted; more than busted;
And I cannot be content;
For, indeed, if I must say it - 
I have not a single cent!
E.A. Barnes.

X
Face to Face.
Face to face, with ancient laws;
Face to face, with customs old;
The master came, a humble man,
Now teaching to unfold.
Face to face, with unbelief;
Face to face, with scorn and pride;
The Savior walked His lonely way,
With foes on every side.
Face to face, with want and sin;
Face to face, with bitter grief;
The Master gave, as none could give,
The balm of sweet relief.

Face to face with cross and thorn;
Face to face, with mortal pain;
The Savior died and by His death,
The soul shall live again.
E.A. Barnes.

Good night, My love.
Sweet are the moments, love,
I spend with thee;
Sweet in the rapture, love,
They bring to me.
Here, at this rustic seat;
Here, where we often meet;
Kiss me, goodnight, my love,
Kiss me, goodnight,
Goodnight, my love.

Life is full of billows,
Swinging o'er the sea;
And with many dangers,
Do they threaten me.
I can see them frowning;
I can hear them roar;
And they fair? would help me,
From the peaceful shore.
Weary is my spirit;
Death is on the wave;
Still I cry to Heaven-
Lord, in mercy save!
E.A. Barnes.

In the Harvest Fields.
In the harvest fields, mid the golden yields,
That we garner, year by year;
As the songs of toil, on their native soil,
See, the reapers, far & near.
See, them pass along, like an army strong,
Laying low the golden grains;
Hear them, sweetly sing, to the Autumn king,
"Tis the harvest-time again!"
Ref:
The harvest-time again;
Yes! yes! the merry harvest-time;
Yes! yes! the happy harvest-time;
'Tis the harvest-time again;
Harvest-time!

In the Harvest Fields.
In the harvest fields, mid the golden yields,
That we garner, year by year;
As the songs of toil, on their native soil,
See, the reapers, far & near.
See, them pass along, like an army strong.
Laying low the golden grains;
Hear them sweetly sing, to the Autumn king,
"Tis the harvest-time again!"
Ref:
The harvest-time again;
Yes!  Yes!  the merry harvest-time;
Yes!  Yes!  the happy harvest-time;
"Tis the harvest-time again,"
Harvest-time!

To me, this stranger man, 
Appeared in sore distress; 
So I brought him food with a bowl of milk, 
And bade him eat & rest.
He took, with trembling hands, 
The welcome drink & food; 
He bowed his head, & then, a blessing rose, 
That spoke his gratitude. 
The simple grace was said; 
The humble meal began; 
When suddenly, a dark & startling change, 
Came over the aged man. 
As one in mortal pain, 
He mutely turned to me; 
While his ashen face, & his stricken form, 
Was terrible to see.

I hastened to his side; 
I raised his silvery head; 
A single look; & lo, I knew it all, - 
The poor, old man was dead!
But ere I called for help,
I stood with bated breath; 
And I left the truth of these solemn words, - 
"In life we are in death." 
E. A. Barnes.

Farewell, brother! Thou art youthful;
To thy care I leave them all;
To this charge, be ever truthful--
Oh! protect them if I fall.
If I fall, I hope to meet thee,
In that world where angels dwell;
There, beloved ones, I'll greet thee;
Home and parents! fare thee well.
E.A. Barnes
